  "texts": [
    "The quantity ∥T ∥ is called the mass or mass norm of T.For a k-current T (k ≥ 1), we denote by ∂T the boundary of T which we recall is defined via:∂T (ω) = T (dω) for C ∞ c (R d, k-1 R d).",
    "A k-current T is called normal if both T and ∂T are of finite mass.",
    "The support of T ∈ D k (R d), spt T, is the least closed set F such that T (ω) = 0 for all ω ∈ C ∞ c (R d, k R d) vanishing in F.Flat chains Given a compact set K ⊂ R d, we define the flat seminorm (with respect to K) of a smooth differential form and the flat norm (with respect to K) of a current by∥ω∥ F k (K) = max{sup x∈K ∥ω(x)∥, sup x∈K ∥dω∥} and ∥T ∥ F k (K) = sup ∥ω∥ F k (K) ≤1 |T (ω)|, respectively.",
    "Note that ∥T ∥ F k (K) < ∞ implies spt T ⊂ K.We recall the equivalent way of defining the flat norm via∥T ∥ F k (K) = inf{∥S∥ + ∥R∥: T = S + ∂R; spt R, spt S ⊂ K}.By F k (K), we denote the set of flat k-chains in K, i.e.",
    "the closure with respect to ∥•∥ F k (K) of normal currents supported inside K. The space F k (K) is equipped with the flat norm, making it into a Banach space."
  ],
